- Had defamatory meaning;
   - Referred to the claimant;
   - Was published to a third party;
   - Caused (or was likely to cause) serious harm to the claimant’s reputation under the *Defamation Act 2013*.  
   Certain defences, such as *qualified privilege* and requirements to prove malice, apply.

- The claim was dismissed in its entirety. The court found:  
  a) No actionable breach of common-law duty;  
  b) No causal link between the failure to request a Construction Phase Plan and the Claimant’s accident;  
  c) The Defendant had met the standard of care expected under the Occupiers’ Liability Act 1957 insofar as he could reasonably rely on the expertise of the Claimant.

- The statutory threshold under section 32A could not realistically be met on the evidence (the 5% recurrence risk was said to be 'purely speculative');  
   - The application was **"far, far too late"**, as the relevant matters (seedling tumour and recurrence risk) had been known since at least March 2018;  
   - It would be **prejudicial** for provisional damages to enter the fray as a remedial option at this stage, as the relevant issues had not fairly been on the agenda for experts.
